<doc id="824435" wikidata="Q2034549" url="?curid=824435" title="Molar refractivity">
<text>Molar refractivity, formula_1, is a measure of the total polarizability of a mole of a substance.

For a perfect dielectric which is made of one type of molecule, the molar refractivity is proportional to the polarizability of a single molecule of the substance. For real materials, intermolecular interactions (the effect of the induced dipole moment of one molecule on the field felt by nearby molecules) give rise to a density dependence.

The molar refractivity is commonly expressed as a sum of components, where the leading order is the value for a perfect dielectric, followed by the density-dependent corrections:

:formula_2

The coefficients formula_3 are called the refractivity virial coefficients. Some research papers are dedicated to finding the values of the subleading coefficients of different substances. In other contexts, the material can be assumed to be approximately perfect, so that the only coefficient of interest is formula_4.

The coefficients depend on the wavelength of the applied field (and on the type and composition of the material), but not on thermodynamic state variables such as temperature or pressure.

The leading order (perfect dielectric) molar refractivity is defined as
:formula_5
where formula_6 is the Avogadro constant and formula_7 is the mean polarizability of a molecule.

Substituting the molar refractivity into the Lorentz-Lorenz formula gives, for gasses
:formula_8

where formula_9 is the refractive index, formula_10 is the pressure of the gas, formula_11 is the universal gas constant, and formula_12 is the (absolute) temperature; the ideal gas law was used here to convert the particle density (appearing in the Lorentz-Lorenz formula) to pressure and temperature.

For a gas, formula_13, so the molar refractivity can be approximated by
:formula_14
The molar refractivity formula_4 does not depend on formula_16, formula_17 or formula_18, since they are not independent quantities.

In terms of density ρ and molecular weight M, it can be shown that:
:formula_19

